  <h1>Getting a Driving Licence in the Gulf 2026</h1>

  <p>Driving in the Gulf is not a luxury, it is a practical necessity. Urban planning across the <a href="/uae/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">UAE</a>, <a href="/qatar/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Qatar</a>, and <a href="/saudi-arabia/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Saudi Arabia</a> has been built around car ownership for decades, and while public transit networks are expanding (the Dubai Metro, Doha Metro, and Riyadh Metro are all operational or nearing completion), they do not yet provide the comprehensive coverage needed for most daily routines. Getting to work, taking children to school, shopping for groceries, and reaching healthcare facilities all involve driving for the majority of the Gulf's expatriate population. Whether you need to convert an existing licence from your home country or learn to drive from scratch through a licensed driving school, understanding the process, costs, and timeline for each country will save you weeks of confusion and potentially thousands of dirhams, riyals, or rials in unnecessary expenses.</p>

  <p>The good news for many professionals arriving from Western countries, and increasingly from parts of Asia and Africa, is that Gulf governments have established mutual recognition agreements that allow straightforward licence conversion without any driving test. The bad news for those whose countries are not on the approved lists is that the driving school process is expensive, time-consuming, and comes with no guarantee of passing on the first attempt. This guide covers the complete process for both pathways in all three Gulf countries, including the specific documents you need, the real costs you should budget for, the common pitfalls that cause delays, and the practical driving knowledge you need to stay safe on Gulf roads.</p>

  <div class="not-prose my-8"><TransportCostEstimator client:visible countryKey="uae" currency="AED" /></div>

  <h2>UAE Driving Licence: The Most Structured System in the Gulf</h2>

  <p>The UAE has the most formalized and well-documented driving licence system in the Gulf, administered by different authorities in each emirate. The Roads and Transport Authority (RTA) handles licensing in Dubai, the Integrated Transport Centre (ITC) covers Abu Dhabi, and each of the remaining five emirates has its own traffic and licensing department. The fundamental distinction that determines your experience is whether your home country appears on the UAE's approved conversion list.</p>

  <h3>Direct Licence Conversion: Approved Countries</h3>

  <p>Approximately 40 countries are on the UAE's approved licence conversion list, and nationals of these countries can exchange their valid foreign licence for a UAE licence without taking any driving test. The list includes the United Kingdom, United States, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Germany, France, Italy, Spain, the Netherlands, Belgium, Austria, Switzerland, Sweden, Denmark, Norway, Finland, Ireland, Portugal, Greece, Japan, South Korea, South Africa, Turkey, Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Romania, and several other European and Commonwealth nations. The list is reviewed periodically by the Ministry of Interior, and countries can be added or removed based on bilateral agreements and driving standards assessments.</p>

  <p>The conversion process requires your original valid foreign driving licence (it must be current, not expired), an official Arabic translation of the licence prepared by a certified legal translator (the translation costs AED 150-200, approximately EUR 38-50), your Emirates ID card, your passport with the residence visa page, two passport-sized photographs with a white background, and an eye test certificate from a SEHA-approved optician or any RTA-approved medical fitness testing center. The eye test costs approximately AED 120 (EUR 30) and takes about 15 minutes. The total cost for the conversion process, including all fees, translation, and eye test, ranges from AED 520 to AED 820 (EUR 130-205) depending on the emirate and whether you use the standard or expedited service.</p>

  <p>Processing typically takes 3-5 working days, though the RTA's smart services portal in Dubai can sometimes complete the process in 24-48 hours. Your original foreign licence is returned to you after the UAE authorities verify its authenticity, which may involve communication with the issuing country's authorities. The UAE licence is valid for a period matching your residency visa, up to a maximum of 10 years, and must be renewed before it expires. Renewal is straightforward and can be done online.</p>

  <h3>Golden Visa Holders: Universal Conversion Privilege</h3>

  <p>One of the less publicized but highly valuable benefits of the UAE Golden Visa is that holders from any nationality can convert their foreign driving licence through the same process as approved-country nationals. This means that an Indian, Filipino, Pakistani, or Egyptian professional who holds a Golden Visa can bypass the driving school requirement entirely, saving thousands of dirhams and months of time. The same privilege extends to family members (spouses and dependents) on the Golden Visa holder's sponsorship. This benefit alone can save a family AED 10,000-20,000 (EUR 2,500-5,000) if multiple members would otherwise need to attend driving school. Given that Golden Visa eligibility now extends to professionals earning AED 30,000 per month or more, property owners with holdings of AED 2 million or above, and various other categories, this driving licence conversion benefit affects a growing segment of the UAE's expatriate population. For a detailed analysis of current Golden Visa eligibility requirements, see our <a href="/uae/visa-guide/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">UAE visa guide</a>.</p>

  <h3>Driving School Route: The Full Process</h3>

  <p>If your home country is not on the approved conversion list and you do not hold a Golden Visa, you must attend a certified driving school and pass a series of tests to obtain a UAE licence. This is the pathway for residents from India, Pakistan, the Philippines, Bangladesh, Egypt, Nepal, Sri Lanka, and many other countries whose nationals make up a large share of the UAE's workforce. The process is thorough, expensive, and can test your patience, but it produces drivers who are familiar with UAE road conditions and traffic regulations.</p>

  <p>The first step is opening a driving file at an RTA-approved school. In Dubai, the major approved schools include Emirates Driving Institute (EDI) on Sheikh Zayed Road, Belhasa Driving Centre in Al Quoz, Galadari Motor Driving Centre in Al Qusais, and Al Ahli Driving School in Muhaisnah. In Abu Dhabi, the Emirates National Driving School and Al Reef Driving Centre are the primary options. File opening requires your Emirates ID, passport with visa page, an eye test certificate, and a no-objection certificate (NOC) from your sponsor if applicable. The file opening fee ranges from AED 200 to AED 300 (EUR 50-75).</p>

  <p>After file opening, you attend 8 mandatory theory lectures covering UAE traffic laws, road signs, roundabout navigation, highway driving rules, and defensive driving principles. The lectures are available in multiple languages including English, Arabic, Hindi, Urdu, Malayalam, and Tagalog. Following the lectures, you take the RTA theory test, which consists of 35 multiple-choice questions delivered on a computer terminal. You need a minimum score of 24 correct answers to pass. The theory course and test cost approximately AED 300 (EUR 75) combined, and you can retake the test for AED 100 (EUR 25) per attempt if you fail.</p>

  <p>Next comes the yard (parking) training phase, which typically involves 20 structured lessons covering parallel parking, hill parking, garage (reverse) parking, and emergency stop procedures. These lessons take place in a controlled yard environment at the driving school. Each lesson lasts 30-40 minutes, and additional lessons cost AED 100-180 (EUR 25-45) each if you need more practice. The yard test evaluates your ability to perform these maneuvers within set parameters, with automated sensors detecting errors. Many candidates require 5-10 additional lessons beyond the standard package before feeling confident enough to attempt the test.</p>

  <p>The final phase is road training and the road test. You receive a minimum of 20 lessons on public roads with a qualified instructor, covering general driving, lane discipline, mirror usage, signal timing, roundabout navigation, highway merging, and various road conditions. The road test is conducted by an RTA examiner in the passenger seat while you drive a predetermined route on public roads. This is where most candidates struggle, as the examiner evaluates not just technical driving ability but also confidence, situational awareness, and adherence to UAE driving conventions. Failing the road test incurs a retake fee of approximately AED 300 (EUR 75) and a mandatory 7-day waiting period. Some candidates report needing 2-4 attempts to pass.</p>

  <p>The total cost for the complete driving school process ranges from AED 5,600 to AED 9,000 (EUR 1,400-2,250) depending on the school you choose, how many additional lessons you require, and how many test attempts it takes to pass. The entire process typically takes 2-6 months from file opening to licence issuance. Budget for the higher end of the cost range if you have limited driving experience, and factor in the time commitment of attending lessons 2-3 times per week during working hours or early evenings.</p>

  <h2>Qatar Driving Licence: Streamlined but Selective</h2>

  <h3>Licence Conversion in Qatar</h3>

  <p>Qatar's licence conversion system is managed by the Traffic Department of the Ministry of Interior. The list of approved countries is similar to the UAE's but not identical, covering most Western European nations, the United States, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Japan, South Korea, and selected other countries. The conversion process requires your valid foreign licence, an Arabic translation by an approved translator, your QID (Qatar ID card), your passport, a medical certificate from a government-approved health center that includes a vision test, and three passport photographs. The total cost is approximately QAR 250-350 (EUR 63-88), and processing takes 5-7 working days.</p>

  <p>One important distinction in Qatar is that the conversion process can only be initiated after your QID has been issued, which typically happens 2-4 weeks after arriving on a work visa. During this period, you can drive using an International Driving Permit (IDP) combined with your original foreign licence. Visitors can use an IDP for up to 6 months, but new residents must obtain a Qatar licence within 7 days of receiving their QID if they intend to continue driving. This tight timeline means you should have all your conversion documents prepared before your QID appointment.</p>

  <h3>Driving School Route in Qatar</h3>

  <p>Residents from countries not on the approved list must attend one of Qatar's certified driving schools. The primary schools are the Qatar Driving School (Al Dafna), Gulf Driving School, and Doha Driving School. The process includes classroom theory sessions, a computer-based theory test at the Traffic Department, practical driving lessons (a minimum of 15-30 hours depending on your assessed skill level), a parking maneuver test, and a road test. Total costs range from QAR 5,000 to QAR 8,000 (EUR 1,250-2,000), making it comparable to the UAE in absolute terms but slightly cheaper on average.</p>

  <p>Qatar imposes additional eligibility requirements that do not exist in the UAE. For some nationalities, a minimum monthly salary of QAR 7,000 (EUR 1,750) is required before a driving licence application will be accepted. This policy is designed to correlate licence issuance with professional status and is enforced through employer salary certificate verification. Students at recognized Qatar universities are exempt from the salary requirement. The minimum age for a light vehicle licence in Qatar is 18 years.</p>

  <p>For daily life in <a href="/qatar/doha/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Doha</a>, having a car is essential for reaching many residential compounds, supermarkets, and leisure facilities. While the Doha Metro serves key corridors including West Bay, The Pearl access points, Education City, and Hamad International Airport, the network does not extend to many residential neighborhoods where expats commonly live, including Al Thumama, Al Wakrah, and parts of Al Rayyan. The combination of affordable fuel at QAR 1.80 (EUR 0.45) per liter and relatively uncongested roads outside rush hour makes driving in Qatar a practical and economical mode of transport.</p>

  <h2>Saudi Arabia Driving Licence: Modernized and Digitized</h2>

  <h3>Licence Conversion in the Kingdom</h3>

  <p>Saudi Arabia's driving licence system has undergone substantial modernization as part of the broader Vision 2030 digital government initiative. The conversion process is managed by the Muroor (General Directorate of Traffic) and can be initiated entirely online through the Absher platform, which serves as the national government services portal. Approximately 30 countries are on Saudi Arabia's approved conversion list, and the list overlaps significantly with the UAE and Qatar lists.</p>

  <p>The required documents include a valid Iqama (residency permit), your original foreign licence with a certified Arabic translation, a medical report from a CCHI-approved clinic (covering a general health assessment and an eye test), four passport photographs, and the application fee of SAR 200-400 (EUR 48-96). Processing takes 7-14 working days, which is longer than the UAE average due to more extensive verification procedures. During the verification period, your original foreign licence may be retained by the Muroor, so plan your transport accordingly. Upon approval, you receive a Saudi driving licence valid for the same duration as your Iqama, up to a maximum of 5 years before renewal.</p>

  <p>Since the historic June 2018 ruling that lifted the ban on women driving, the licence application process in Saudi Arabia has been identical for men and women. Women from countries on the approved conversion list exchange their existing licences through the same process described above. Women from non-approved countries attend one of the accredited driving schools, which now operate mixed-gender or female-only training programs in all major cities.</p>

  <h3>Driving School Route in Saudi Arabia</h3>

  <p>Saudi Arabia's driving school process is generally faster and cheaper than the UAE equivalent, reflecting the kingdom's push to make private vehicle ownership accessible as an alternative to the employer-provided transportation that many companies historically offered. Major accredited schools include the Saudi Driving School in <a href="/saudi-arabia/riyadh/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Riyadh</a>, <a href="/saudi-arabia/jeddah/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Jeddah</a> Driving School, Dallah Driving School (multiple locations), and the Eastern Province Driving School in <a href="/saudi-arabia/dammam/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Dammam</a>. The curriculum includes theory classes, a computer-based theory test, simulator training sessions (some schools have invested in advanced driving simulators that replicate Saudi road conditions), practical in-car lessons (10-30 hours depending on your package and experience), a parking assessment, and a road test conducted on public roads.</p>

  <p>The total cost ranges from SAR 2,200 to SAR 5,500 (EUR 530-1,320), making it the most affordable driving school process among the three Gulf countries. Basic packages with minimum lesson hours start at the lower end, while premium packages with extended training, simulator time, and guaranteed test retakes approach the upper limit. The entire process typically takes 1-4 months. Language support is available in Arabic, English, Urdu, Hindi, and other languages depending on the school location. Evening and weekend class options have expanded significantly since 2020, accommodating working professionals who cannot attend during standard business hours.</p>

  <h3>The Saher Traffic System</h3>

  <p>Every driver in Saudi Arabia must understand the Saher automated traffic monitoring system, which uses an extensive network of cameras installed on highways and urban roads to detect speeding, red light violations, lane violations, illegal U-turns, and mobile phone use while driving. Fines are issued automatically and appear on your Absher account, typically within 24-48 hours of the infraction. The fine schedule ranges from SAR 300 (EUR 72) for minor speeding (exceeding the limit by less than 20 km/h) to SAR 6,000 (EUR 1,440) for serious violations such as running a red light or driving the wrong way on a highway. Accumulated unpaid fines create escalating problems: they can prevent Iqama renewal, block vehicle registration processes, and restrict international travel through the exit permit system. Regularly checking your Absher account and settling fines promptly is essential. The Absher app provides push notifications for new fines, making it straightforward to stay on top of your record.</p>

  <h2>International Driving Permits: Temporary Bridge, Not Long-Term Solution</h2>

  <p>An International Driving Permit (IDP) issued by your home country's motoring authority serves as a temporary authorization to drive in all three Gulf countries. The IDP is valid for tourists and business visitors, and it is accepted by car rental agencies across the region. However, the IDP is explicitly a transitional document for residents. In the UAE, you are expected to obtain a local licence once your Emirates ID is issued, which typically happens within 2-4 weeks of receiving your residence visa. In Qatar, the transition window is 7 days from receiving your QID. In Saudi Arabia, the expectation is that you apply for a local licence within 3 months of Iqama issuance, though enforcement timelines vary.</p>

  <p>Driving on an expired IDP or on a foreign licence after the transition period has elapsed creates insurance complications that can be financially devastating. If you are involved in an accident while driving without a valid local licence, your insurance company may deny the claim, leaving you personally liable for vehicle damage, medical costs, and third-party compensation. Given that accident repair costs in the Gulf can easily reach AED 20,000-50,000 (EUR 5,000-12,500) for a moderate collision, and medical liability can be far higher, the financial risk of delaying your licence conversion or driving school enrollment is substantial.</p>

  <h2>Car Insurance: Mandatory and Variable</h2>

  <p>Car insurance is legally required in all three Gulf countries, and you cannot register a vehicle or renew its registration without valid insurance documentation. The two main categories are third-party liability insurance (the legal minimum, covering damage you cause to other people and their property) and comprehensive insurance (covering damage to your own vehicle as well). For expatriates, comprehensive insurance is strongly recommended, particularly in the first year when you are still adapting to local driving conditions and road culture.</p>

  <p>Annual insurance premiums vary based on the vehicle's market value, the driver's age and nationality, claims history, and the coverage level selected. For a standard sedan valued at AED 60,000-80,000 (EUR 15,000-20,000), comprehensive insurance typically costs AED 2,000-3,500 (EUR 500-875) per year in the UAE, QAR 1,500-3,000 (EUR 375-750) in Qatar, and SAR 1,500-3,500 (EUR 360-840) in Saudi Arabia. Third-party insurance is considerably cheaper, starting from AED 700 (EUR 175) in the UAE, QAR 500 (EUR 125) in Qatar, and SAR 700 (EUR 168) in Saudi Arabia. Online comparison platforms including Yallacompare in the UAE, PolicyBazaar across the UAE and Saudi Arabia, and direct insurer websites in Qatar can help you find competitive rates. Many insurers offer discounts for safe driving records, garage parking, and anti-theft device installation.</p>

  <h2>Fuel Costs and Running a Vehicle</h2>

  <p>One of the genuine advantages of car ownership in the Gulf is the relatively low fuel cost compared to European or North American markets. Petrol prices in 2026 stand at approximately AED 2.90 (EUR 0.73) per liter in the UAE, QAR 1.80 (EUR 0.45) per liter in Qatar, and SAR 2.18 (EUR 0.52) per liter in Saudi Arabia. Diesel prices are lower still in all three countries. For a typical commuter driving 1,500 km per month in a mid-size sedan consuming 8-10 liters per 100 km, monthly fuel costs range from AED 400-600 (EUR 100-150) in the UAE to QAR 250-400 (EUR 63-100) in Qatar and SAR 300-450 (EUR 72-108) in Saudi Arabia. These figures are a fraction of what the same driving pattern would cost in Western Europe, where fuel at EUR 1.80-2.00 per liter would produce monthly bills of EUR 250-350.</p>

  <p>Beyond fuel, the ongoing costs of car ownership include annual insurance renewal, vehicle registration (linked to inspection and fine clearance in all three countries), regular servicing at dealer or independent workshops, tire replacement (essential twice yearly due to heat degradation, particularly for summer and winter compound tires), and parking fees in commercial areas. Toll systems operate in Dubai (Salik, AED 4 per toll gate) and on some Saudi Arabian highways. The total annual cost of owning and running a mid-range sedan, excluding the purchase or lease payment itself, typically falls between AED 8,000-15,000 (EUR 2,000-3,750), QAR 6,000-12,000 (EUR 1,500-3,000), or SAR 7,000-14,000 (EUR 1,680-3,360) depending on the country and your driving patterns.</p>

  <p>Purchasing a used car is a common and economical choice for expats who do not want to commit to a new vehicle. Reliable used models from Toyota, Nissan, Hyundai, and Kia are widely available in the AED 25,000-70,000 (EUR 6,250-17,500) range across all three countries. Pre-purchase inspection services, such as those offered by the Automobile and Touring Club of the UAE (ATCUE) or similar organizations, cost AED 300-500 (EUR 75-125) and can identify hidden mechanical issues before you commit to a purchase. Car leasing is an increasingly popular alternative, with monthly payments starting from AED 1,500-2,500 (EUR 360-600) for a basic sedan including maintenance and insurance in some packages.</p>

  <h2>Practical Driving in the Gulf: What Nobody Tells You Before You Arrive</h2>

  <p>Gulf driving culture has its own distinct characteristics that can surprise new arrivals, even experienced drivers from countries with well-established road safety records. Understanding these patterns is not about cultural criticism but about practical safety preparation.</p>

  <p>Speed limits are generally 60-80 km/h on urban roads and 100-140 km/h on highways, with radar cameras extensively deployed across all three countries. The UAE operates a tolerance buffer (typically 20 km/h above the posted limit on highways before a fine is triggered), while Saudi Arabia's Saher system and Qatar's enforcement cameras have tighter thresholds. Lane discipline varies considerably from Western European norms. Sudden lane changes without indicating, undertaking on the right, and merging aggressively at highway exits are common behaviors that you need to anticipate without imitating. Tailgating, particularly by large SUVs and luxury vehicles on the fast lane of highways, is a persistent hazard. The correct response is to move to a slower lane when safe to do so, not to brake suddenly or engage in confrontational driving.</p>

  <p>Roundabouts are a dominant feature of Gulf road design, and understanding right-of-way rules at multi-lane roundabouts is essential for daily driving. In the UAE, traffic already on the roundabout has right of way. In Saudi Arabia, some roundabouts have been replaced by signal-controlled intersections, but many remain. Qatar's road network was extensively upgraded and redesigned ahead of the 2022 FIFA World Cup, resulting in modern, well-marked highways with clear signage.</p>

  <p>Several seasonal factors affect driving safety. During Ramadan, the period just before sunset (Iftar time) sees a noticeable increase in aggressive driving as fasting drivers rush to reach home or a restaurant. The roads become noticeably quieter during the Iftar period itself, then busy again in the late evening. Summer heat from June through September affects both vehicle performance and driver behavior. Tires degrade faster on superheated asphalt, engine cooling systems are tested to their limits, and driver fatigue increases during daytime hours. Winter months from November through March bring pleasant driving conditions but also occasional fog in coastal areas, particularly in Dubai, Abu Dhabi, and the Eastern Province of Saudi Arabia, which can reduce visibility to below 50 meters and has historically caused major multi-vehicle pileups on highways.</p>

  <h2>Road Safety and Emergency Procedures</h2>

  <p>Knowing what to do after an accident is essential. In all three Gulf countries, the general emergency number is 999 for police, ambulance, and fire services. The UAE has introduced digital accident reporting for minor collisions (no injuries, two vehicles, damage below a threshold) through the Dubai Police app and Abu Dhabi Police app, which allows you to move your vehicle to the roadside and submit photos and details through the app rather than waiting for police to arrive. This system speeds up the process considerably and prevents the traffic congestion that used to result from two cars blocking a lane for hours waiting for a police report.</p>

  <p>In Qatar, the Metrash2 app offers accident reporting capabilities, and the police will attend the scene for accidents involving injuries or significant damage. In Saudi Arabia, the Najm app handles accident reporting and insurance claim initiation for insured vehicles. In all three countries, the critical rule is: do not move your vehicle from the accident position until either police have arrived and authorized it or you have completed the digital reporting process and received confirmation. Moving a vehicle before documentation can invalidate your insurance claim and may even shift legal liability. Always take photographs of the scene, all vehicles involved, licence plates, damage, and any visible road conditions before anything is moved.</p>

  <p>Mobile phone use while driving carries heavy fines across the Gulf: AED 800 (EUR 200) in the UAE plus 4 black points on your licence, SAR 500-900 (EUR 120-216) in Saudi Arabia, and QAR 500 (EUR 125) in Qatar. Repeat offenses can lead to licence suspension. Hands-free calling through Bluetooth is permitted in all three countries. Drink driving penalties are severe across the Gulf, where alcohol consumption is either restricted (UAE, Qatar) or prohibited (Saudi Arabia). In the UAE, a blood alcohol level above 0% while driving results in arrest, vehicle impoundment, potential imprisonment, and possible deportation. There is no tolerance threshold. In Saudi Arabia, where alcohol is entirely prohibited, any driving impairment carries criminal penalties. The message is unambiguous: do not drive after consuming any amount of alcohol in any Gulf country.</p>

  <h2>Summary: Which Country Is Cheapest and Fastest?</h2>

  <p>For licence conversion from an approved country, Saudi Arabia is the cheapest at SAR 200-400 (EUR 48-96), followed by Qatar at QAR 250-350 (EUR 63-88), and the UAE at AED 520-820 (EUR 130-205). The UAE has the fastest processing at 3-5 days, Qatar takes 5-7 days, and Saudi Arabia takes 7-14 days. For the full driving school route, Saudi Arabia is again the most affordable at SAR 2,200-5,500 (EUR 530-1,320) and the fastest at 1-4 months. Qatar sits in the middle at QAR 5,000-8,000 (EUR 1,250-2,000) over 2-4 months. The UAE is the most expensive at AED 5,600-9,000 (EUR 1,400-2,250) over 2-6 months. However, the UAE's Golden Visa universal conversion privilege makes it the best option for professionals from non-approved countries who hold or can obtain Golden Visa status, effectively eliminating the driving school requirement entirely regardless of nationality.</p>

  <p>Regardless of which country you are in, prioritize obtaining your local licence as early as possible after arrival. The combination of insurance validity, legal compliance, and practical independence that comes with holding a local Gulf driving licence is one of the most important foundations for a smooth and productive expatriate life in the region. For a complete overview of living costs including transportation, see our country-specific guides for the <a href="/uae/cost-of-living/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">UAE</a>, <a href="/qatar/cost-of-living/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Qatar</a>, and <a href="/saudi-arabia/cost-of-living/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Saudi Arabia</a>.</p>

